# Reflection

One of the main challenges in this assignment was translating requirements and use cases into user stories. 
It required simplifying technical requirements into user-focused statements while ensuring clarity and value.

Another challenge was prioritizing the backlog using the MoSCoW method. 
Deciding which features were essential (Must-have) versus optional (Could-have) required careful consideration of system goals and stakeholder needs.

Estimating effort using story points was also difficult, as it required making assumptions about development complexity without actual implementation experience.

Sprint planning presented challenges in selecting a realistic number of tasks that could be completed within a two-week period. 
Balancing ambition with feasibility was important to ensure achievable goals.

Additionally, working alone meant acting as multiple roles (developer, product owner, and tester), which made decision-making more complex.

Overall, this assignment improved understanding of Agile methodologies, backlog prioritization, and sprint planning in software development.
